irway lumen","Increased mucus hydration","Enhanced mucociliary clearance","Reduced work of breathing"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn cystic fibrosis, mutations in the CFTR gene lead to defective chloride channels. This results in \u003Cstrong\u003Edecreased epithelial chloride transport\u003C/strong\u003E and reduced bicarbonate secretion into the airway lumen. The ion transport defect prevents proper hydration of the airway surface liquid, making it impossible to have \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased water efflux into airway lumen\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe dehydrated airway surface leads to thick, sticky mucus rather than \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased mucus hydration\u003C/strong\u003E. This impairs \u003Cstrong\u003Eenhanced mucociliary clearance\u003C/strong\u003E, as the cilia cannot effectively beat in the thick mucus. The increased mucus viscosity and airway obstruction leads to increased, not \u003Cstrong\u003Ereduced work of breathing\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese changes create an environment conducive to chronic infection and inflammation, leading to progressive lung damage.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cystic fibrosis is caused by defective CFTR channels leading to reduced chloride and bicarbonate secretion into airways.","Reduced ion transport in cystic fibrosis results in thick, dehydrated mucus that impairs mucociliary clearance.","The thick mucus in cystic fibrosis increases work of breathing and susceptibility to infections."],"references":["Savant A, Lyman B, Bojanowski C, Upadia J. Cystic Fibrosis. 2001 Mar 26 [updated 2024 Aug 8]. In: Adam MP, Feldman J, Mirzaa GM, Pagon RA, Wallace SE, Amemiya A, editors. GeneReviews\u00ae [Internet]. Seattle (WA): University of Washington, Seattle; 1993\u20132024. PMID: 20301428.","Shteinberg M, Haq IJ, Polineni D, Davies JC. Cystic fibrosis. Lancet. 2021 Jun 5;397(10290):2195-2211. doi: 10.1016/S0140-6736(20)32542-3. PMID: 34090606.","Mason, R. J., Broaddus, V. C., Martin, T. R., King, T. E., Schraufnagel, D., Murray, J. F., \u0026 Nadel, J. A. (2010). Murray and Nadel\u0027s textbook of respiratory medicine E-book: 2-volume set. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46926"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15461"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/46926"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-15T16:21:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-15T16:21:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8152"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61475"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{